Keeping the estimate low is a tactic, of course. Christie=E2=80=99s is not =
only trying to attract bidders to the Picabia
but also signaling to potential consignors that these will be sales to watc=
h. Right now, no one believes the slow art market is a reflection of buyers=
 lacking the money; instead it=E2=80=99s a matter of enthusiasm, estimates,=
 and momentum. Amid this P.R. blitz, Christie=E2=80=99s is hoping to revers=
e the lethargy. They=E2=80=99re planting a flag. =E2=80=9CEverything in the=
 near future points to a weakening of London,=E2=80=9D one Parisian collect=
or told me. =E2=80=9CBut not necessarily a strengthening of Paris (unstable=
 political situation with the far left pointing its tax-greedy snout=E2=80=
=A6).=E2=80=9D But the new French government has only just been elected and=
, for the moment, at least one prominent private dealer who moved his base =
of operations from New York to Paris believes the capital of the luxury ind=
ustry is as close as it gets to being a tax haven for art.

There is also a large inventory of Modern artworks held in old Parisian col=
lections. That gives the auction houses a target-rich environment to
tap for sales. Calls are being made right now, before everyone gets out of =
dodge to avoid the madness of the Olympics, because contracts will have to =
be signed by early September at the latest. The bonus for moving sales to P=
aris is that the auction houses will save on the cost of shipping, which ha=
s become meaningful even on short hops between France and the United Kingdo=
m.

Londontownies

The same collector also estimates that the base of local buyers is probably=
 10 times larger in Paris than London. For better or worse, London had beco=
me a second or third home to non-domiciled expatriates who weren=E2=80=99t =
paying taxes on money earned abroad. Indeed, it=E2=80=99s been estimated th=
at, at the height of non-dom residency, 30 percent of Londoners making over=
 =C2=A35 million were non-doms, and that up to 10 percent of London residen=
ts had non-dom status. Since Brexit in 2016, nearly half of that non-dom po=
pulation has left. Moreover, the newly installed Labour government has said=
 they plan to tax non-dom earnings to raise about =C2=A33 billion for the n=
ational health service. Another issue dogging the London market is Brexit-i=
nduced bureaucratic red tape around imports and exports for the galleries, =
which lack the staff to handle the paperwork overload.

Beyond the new taxes and red tape, it=E2=80=99s undeniable that London=E2=
=80=99s museums are feeling a bit tired. =E2=80=9CLondon has become a provi=
ncial city in this respect,=E2=80=9D the collector told me. Of course, Lond=
on still has the National Gallery, the Tate and Tate Modern, the Wallace Co=
llection, the British Museum, the Serpentine and Whitechapel galleries, and=
 lots of commercial galleries. But there=E2=80=99s a lack of excitement in =
London=E2=80=99s museum shows. Last year for Frieze, in October, the Nation=
al Gallery=E2=80=99s generational Frans Hals show was sparsely attended. Ye=
t, across the channel, the rivalry between Pinault and Arnault=E2=80=99s ve=
ry different private museums has been producing a wealth of excitement. Las=
t year, Arnault=E2=80=99s Fondation Louis Vuitton=E2=80=99s Mark Rothko ret=
rospective=E2=80=94which was dubbed =E2=80=9Cthe impossible show=E2=80=9D b=
ecause the insurance fees were above the ability of a public institution to=
 bear=E2=80=94was packed for months. (This year, they=E2=80=99re planning a=
 major
retrospective of Tom Wesselmann and Pop art.) Pinault=E2=80=99s Bourse de C=
ommerce museum regularly runs provocative and, occasionally, market-moving =
surveys of a wide range of Contemporary artists. Last October, Paris=E2=80=
=99s other museums seemed to calibrate their shows perfectly to the tastes =
and interests of the public and the market alike. =E2=80=9CObviously, Pinau=
lt and Arnault have a huge influence and financial clout that plays out not=
 only in their museums, but also in state museums like Orsay and the Louvre=
,=E2=80=9D the collector said.

=E2=80=9COne downside that has been discussed amongst collectors,=E2=80=9D =
London dealer Lock Kresler observed of Paris, =E2=80=9Cis that there are al=
most too many distractions, meaning that collectors may only come to the fa=
ir once as part of their laundry list of sites and shopping to do in the ci=
ty.=E2=80=9D Adding higher-quality works with international appeal to the P=
aris auctions will only further distract buyers from the fair, of course.

And no matter what London dealers say, in terms of quality of expertise, ex=
perience, and know-how, London and Paris are equivalent. Though Kresler poi=
nts out that opening a Parisian branch of an international dealership isn=
=E2=80=99t as easy as many think, especially when it comes to staffing.

=E2=80=9CRight now, there is undoubtedly a move toward Paris at every level=
, except old masters,=E2=80=9D the collector concluded. =E2=80=9CBut again,=
 we are talking of rather small markets when compared to New York.=E2=80=9D=
 Paris has a long way to go before it is a counterweight to London. Already=
 it looks like sales of Surrealism and Italian Post-war and Contemporary ar=
t will be moving toward Paris and away from London. But much of the rest of=
 the growth in Paris will come from places like Milan and Amsterdam, not th=
e city=E2=80=99s traditional rival to the north.

And let=E2=80=99s not forget that both auction houses are now owned by Fren=
ch nationals. Sotheby=E2=80=99s owner Patrick Drahi is
nowhere near as wealthy as Arnault or even Pinault, of course, and yet his =
desire to have a large flagship location in Paris may be a business decisio=
n as much as a point of personal pride.

