x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Last year, the Octo=
ber sales held in Paris to coincide with Art Basel=E2=80=99s Paris Plus art=
 fair were an unexpected success. Sotheby=E2=80=99s was able to post strong=
 numbers for works by <b>Ren=C3=A9 Magritte</b>, <b>Lucio Fontana, Pierre S=
oulages</b>, and <b>Frantisek Kupka</b> in their Modern sale, while the sin=
gle-owner <b>Pauline Karpidas</b> sale of the contents of her Hydra home pr=
oduced a rousing =E2=82=AC35.5 million. Christie=E2=80=99s also did quite w=
ell: It sold <b>Francois-Xavier Lalanne</b>=E2=80=99s <i>Rhinocretaire I</i=
> for =E2=82=AC18.3 million, a record price for the artist. The auction hou=
se also sold works from the collection of <b>Anne</b> and <b>Wolfgang Titze=
</b> for =E2=82=AC27.7 million, and the La Colombe d=E2=80=99Or hotel=E2=80=
=99s<b> Joan Mir=C3=B3</b> for =E2=82=AC20.7 million. <br/><br/>This year, =
the auction houses have already begun announcing lots for the Paris sales, =
even
though they remain a full quarter away. Of course, some of the emphasis on =
Paris is a reflection of the quirks of the calendar. It=E2=80=99s July and =
the Contemporary market is still contracting, which means the midseason sal=
es in New York will not have publicity-worthy lots. And despite the fact th=
at Christie=E2=80=99s and Sotheby=E2=80=99s will, for the first time, be ho=
lding their Hong Kong sales in close proximity to each other in late Septem=
ber, the Asian market is in hibernation. But with the marketing upgrade of =
Paris+ (no, it=E2=80=99s not a streaming service) to Art Basel Paris and th=
e tailwind of attention many expect after the Olympics, along with the cons=
istent push from the <b>Arnault</b> and <b>Pinault</b> clans to draw attent=
ion to the city as the capital of the art-luxury industrial complex, there=
=E2=80=99s a dawning recognition that Paris will be playing a bigger role i=
n the art trade=E2=80=94and its late October pit stop on the international =
swirl will become a signature annual event.
<br/><br/>Sotheby=E2=80=99s, of course, has announced that its new, much la=
rger, Paris headquarters will open in October, which will bring it physical=
ly closer to its rivals. Just 270 meters from Christie=E2=80=99s and Gagosi=
an, on one end=E2=80=94with Skarstedt, Perrotin, Almine Rech, White Cube, M=
ariane Ibrahim, and Tornabuoni in between=E2=80=94Sotheby=E2=80=99s will an=
chor the other end of an Avenue Matignon superblock.<br/></td>
