         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s4">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The same collector =
also estimates that the base of local buyers is probably 10 times larger in=
 Paris than London. For better or worse, London had become a second or thir=
d home to non-domiciled expatriates who weren=E2=80=99t paying taxes on mon=
ey earned abroad. Indeed, it=E2=80=99s been estimated that, at the height o=
f non-dom residency, 30 percent of Londoners making over =C2=A35 million we=
re non-doms, and that up to 10 percent of London residents had non-dom stat=
us. Since Brexit in 2016, nearly half of that non-dom population has left. =
Moreover, the newly installed Labour government has said they plan to tax n=
on-dom earnings to raise about =C2=A33 billion for the national health serv=
ice.  Another issue dogging the London market is Brexit-induced bureaucrati=
c red tape around imports and exports for the galleries, which lack the sta=
ff to handle the paperwork overload.
<br/><br/>Beyond the new taxes and red tape, it=E2=80=99s undeniable that L=
ondon=E2=80=99s museums are feeling a bit tired. =E2=80=9CLondon has become=
 a provincial city in this respect,=E2=80=9D the collector told me. Of cour=
se, London still has the National Gallery, the Tate and Tate Modern, the Wa=
llace Collection, the British Museum, the Serpentine and Whitechapel galler=
ies, and lots of commercial galleries. But there=E2=80=99s a lack of excite=
ment in London=E2=80=99s museum shows. Last year for Frieze, in October, th=
e National Gallery=E2=80=99s generational <b>Frans Hals</b> show was sparse=
ly attended. Yet, across the channel, the rivalry between Pinault and Arnau=
lt=E2=80=99s very different private museums has been producing a wealth of =
excitement. Last year, Arnault=E2=80=99s Fondation Louis Vuitton=E2=80=99s =
<b>Mark Rothko </b>retrospective=E2=80=94which was dubbed =E2=80=9Cthe impo=
ssible show=E2=80=9D because the insurance fees were above the ability of a=
 public institution to bear=E2=80=94was packed for months. (This year, they=
=E2=80=99re planning a major
retrospective of <b>Tom Wesselmann</b> and Pop art.) Pinault=E2=80=99s Bour=
se de Commerce museum regularly runs provocative and, occasionally, market-=
moving surveys of a wide range of Contemporary artists. Last October, Paris=
=E2=80=99s other museums seemed to calibrate their shows perfectly to the t=
astes and interests of the public and the market alike. =E2=80=9CObviously,=
 Pinault and Arnault have a huge influence and financial clout that plays o=
ut not only in their museums, but also in state museums like Orsay and the =
Louvre,=E2=80=9D the collector said.<br/><br/>=E2=80=9COne downside that ha=
s been discussed amongst collectors,=E2=80=9D London dealer <b>Lock Kresler=
</b> observed of Paris, =E2=80=9Cis that there are almost too many distract=
ions, meaning that collectors may only come to the fair once as part of the=
ir laundry list of sites and shopping to do in the city.=E2=80=9D Adding hi=
gher-quality works with international appeal to the Paris auctions will onl=
y further distract buyers from the fair, of course.
<br/><br/>And no matter what London dealers say, in terms of quality of exp=
ertise, experience, and know-how, London and Paris are equivalent. Though K=
resler points out that opening a Parisian branch of an international dealer=
ship isn=E2=80=99t as easy as many think, especially when it comes to staff=
ing. <br/><br/>=E2=80=9CRight now, there is undoubtedly a move toward Paris=
 at every level, except old masters,=E2=80=9D the collector concluded. =E2=
=80=9CBut again, we are talking of rather small markets when compared to Ne=
w York.=E2=80=9D Paris has a long way to go before it is a counterweight to=
 London. Already it looks like sales of Surrealism and Italian Post-war and=
 Contemporary art will be moving toward Paris and away from London. But muc=
h of the rest of the growth in Paris will come from places like Milan and A=
msterdam, not the city=E2=80=99s traditional rival to the north. <br/><br/>=
And let=E2=80=99s not forget that both auction houses are now owned by Fren=
ch nationals. Sotheby=E2=80=99s owner <b>Patrick Drahi</b> is
nowhere near as wealthy as Arnault or even Pinault, of course, and yet his =
desire to have a large flagship location in Paris may be a business decisio=
n as much as a point of personal pride. <br/></td>
         </tr>
